Message.Title: Offer on Dell falls $3.9B short
Message.Msg: From today's SEC Live filings digest: Southeastern Asset Management and billionaire investor Carl Icahn made an offer to purchase the company that fell $3.9B short of the target amount Dellâ€™s special committee was hoping for. The proposal promised that Dell shareholders would retain their current stake in the company plus $12.00 cash per share owned or additional shares. A Dell special committee, formed in August when Michael Dell disclosed he was considering taking the company private has conducted several price negotiations and contacting potential buyers, all of which have not resulted in a deal. Currently, Dell favors the offer made by Silver Lake Partners and Michael Dell that would take the company private for $24.4B or $13.65 per share. Dell shareholders are set to vote on the Silver Lake/Michael Dell offer on July 18th.
